NURSES: You not only have a right, but an obligation to refuse unsafe assignments ⁣
⁣
Do it BEFORE you take report/say hi to the patient/take them to the bathroom/look at their chart⁣
⁣
Reasons to refuse an unsafe assignment:⁣
• Too many patients⁣
• Patient acuity ⁣
• Lack of support staff⁣
• Inadequate training⁣
• Lack of supplies/equipment⁣
⁣
What to do:⁣
• Know your states rights on duty to refuse vs patient abandonment ⁣
• Express to your charge nurse, on duty manager verbally that you do not feel comfortable accepting the assignment, with the reasons above⁣
• Send an email to all members leadership and summarize the situation, state why you are refusing with the above reasons referenced ⁣
• Ask for your coworkers support. Another nurse agreeing they also wouldn’t accept that assignment for the same reason is powerful. ⁣
• Stay calm, respectful, but firm. You are doing this because it’s a patient safety risk. There is nothing more to add other than you know the law in your state. You feel this is a risk to the patient. And you will not be pressured to risk your license. ⁣
⁣
Know:⁣
That unfortunately even though it absolutely is your duty to refuse an unsafe assignment, the hospital might try to retaliate against you for doing so. They can claim insubordination or other false claims to bully and intimidate others from joining you. The best way to combat this, is to stand in solidarity with each other. Other nurses refusing this or other unsafe assignments, having other workers on your unit providing written statements supporting your action, and/or speaking out IN THE MOMENT against the person trying to bully you to take the assignment is extremely powerful. ⁣
⁣
Nurses are literally fired for completing their duty to refuse an unsafe assignment. This must stop. Let’s start a culture change. 💪⁣

Classism and ⚪️ supremacy in nursing: I was a low income nursing student, I became an LPN. ⁣
⁣
I went to an accredited LPN to ADN school aimed at nursing students working fulltime. The state of California rejects students from my school from licensing because they allowed us to take our classes and clinicals separatly as long as we were working fulltime. ⁣
⁣
My story is not unique. Low income nursing students and women of color are primarily affected by policies like this. ⁣
⁣
It doesnt matter that I went on to get my BSN, or if i even got a DNP. It doesn’t matter that I worked in the COVID ICU and was called a hero in March 2020. California will not let me work in their state. ⁣
⁣
Policies like this must change. ⁣
⁣

I’m Abby, a registered nurse, and a nursing union organizer with SEIU121RN. 

California law mandates a safe number of patients for every nurse. But that law isn’t being followed. 

During the COVID-19 State of Emergency, the California Department of Public Health stopped enforcing safe staffing laws. 

Hospitals used the crisis to cut corners, reducing hospital staffing to the barebones, that means there weren’t enough of us, to care for you. 

The California COVID19 state of emergency ends 2/28.

We are calling on CDPH to put safe staffing laws back in place -  with investigations & fines. No more excuses, our patients can’t wait. 

Text “CDPH” to 787-753 to join our  campaign. 

Safe Staffing Saves Lives. Patients can’t wait.

SAFE STARFING RALLY: 1600 Rose Ave, Oxnard CA @10:30am — Then March to CDPH! ⁣
⁣
During the COVID-19 State of Emergency, CDPH stopped enforcing safe staffing laws. Hospitals used the crisis to cut corners wherever they could, putting our patients and our licenses at risk. ⁣
⁣
The emergency order ends on February 28. That means all safe staffing laws should be back in place with investigations and fines to back them up.⁣
⁣

Each day Education works at @lausdschools serves 680,000 meals, clean 710 square miles, and serve 11,200 special needs students. But those workers are grossly underpaid and undervalued. ⁣
⁣
The average Education Worker works 5.4 hours a day and earns $25k a year. ⁣
⁣
In bargaining, LAUSD has offered wage increases that will only put workers deeper into poverty. ⁣
⁣
Ed Workers are demanding respect on the job and dignified pay. Too many Ed workers report experiencing hunger or homelessness or both. ⁣
⁣
64% Latino 20% Black and 74% Women. ⁣
⁣
Shame on LAUSD for not resolving this four years ago during the pandemic when workers accepted delaying bargaining and risked their lives to hand out over 140 million meals & tens of thousands of computers & tablets for remote learning. This, before effective treatments or vaccines. ⁣
⁣
It is time the district stopped taking these essential education workers for granted. ⁣
Education workers are 40% of LAUSD workers yet our pay only represents 7% of LAUSD’s $12.6 Billion annual budget. ⁣
⁣
Workers are demanding a 30% raise over 3 years plus a $2 equity adjustment. This is fair. For example, Ed workers earning $25k would go to $36K - and improve the lives of tens of thousands of Angelinos.⁣
⁣
Stand with Education workers and call on@LAUSDSupt Carvalho to pay a living wage to Education Workers.⁣
⁣
Sign the petition demanding @lausdsup Carvalho respect Ed Workers and pay a living wage. Link in story. ⁣

Nurses are in solidarity with @wgawest. There was randomly a strikeline on an @azizansari project near my house attempting to push the project forward, regardless of the strike. I went to chat with the organizers, and walked the line. A very cool part of their action: the Teamsters union commits to not drive trucks past entrances that are staffed with picket signs. Teamsters deliver most of the equipment and supplies to production, the solidarity effectively shuts down the days work, even when the writers wouldn’t be necessary to be in person. Writers cannot make a living wage, even though their projects make millions of dollars, and they would traditionally receive perpetuity. Their work is being threatened by AI, even though AI was programmed by writers work. And mostly, their work is not being valued as a serious profession, that deserves respect and compensation. I hope they get everything they deserve and more 🪧 ✊
My take on the NYSNA nurses strike 💪

Workplace Violence Prevention: three healthcare workers were stabbed in an emergency department in Encino California. One year ago, they were calling for workplace violence prevention before the stabbing occurred. In the last year, the hospital has only installed one metal detector. Hospitals don’t like things like metal detectors, because they lower patient satisfaction scores, impacting their reimbursements. We need to start pushing what works. Safe staffing as violence prevention works. Panic buttons work. Weapon screening works. Separate tracks for patients with minor complaints, and eliminating long wait times work. We need workplace violence protection on a national level.

Nurses stand in solidarity with @wgawest & @sagaftra Bob Iger makes $78,000 A DAY. This is the same fight we face in nursing. Greedy, out of touch executives skimming money from the labor of people who actually DO THE WORK. 

Bob’s folks are obviously pleased with this job he’s doing because his contract was extended to 2026, raising his annual compensation to $31 million. 

Only 14% of actors represented by the SAG-AFTRA guild earn the minimum $26,470 necessary to qualify for health insurance. 

We must take back all institutions that do not support the working class. No one should be making more money PER DAY, than some make ALL YEAR (probably working much harder)
Andrew Witty made 20 million last year alone by denying treatment to sick patients who paid their premiums. A for-profit system will never be patient centered.

The CEO of CHOP, who is also a nurse, received $7.7 million in compensation in 2021.

Nonprofit hospitals receive money from the state and the federal government to provide charity care.

They’re not providing charity care, we all know this. 

That’s why our patients are going bankrupt.
They also receive donations from the general public and wealthy people in their area, so those folks can write that off as a tax deduction.

All of that money is tax exempt. 

Not to mention the reimbursements from Medicare/Medicaid. 

Yet, there is no cap on executive salaries in non-profit hospitals. 

These are taxpayer funds. How is this legal?

There’s been a couple of proposals in the past to cap executive salary at non-profit hospitals. It is largely failed. It was actually enacted in New York a bunch of years ago by Cuomo as an executive order, and you better believe those CEOs organized and they got rid of it.

Say it with me now healthcare workers and patients, we are calling on our legislators to cap executive salary at non-profit hospitals.

This is money laundering.

#foryou #fyp #nursesoftiktok #Unionnurses #nurseproblems #corruption #nurselife

Street harassment is not limited to overt sexual comments. It can be subtle. It can start with a simple, good morning, and quickly become a situation you don’t want to be in. 

Don’t talk to strangers unless you want to. Don’t let people shame you into a conversation. I don’t feel entitled to a strangers time, and I’m guessing you don’t either.
Oh. Well this. Is my bad.

Vote blue no matter who?? No. I don’t care if I fundamentally agree with everything a politician is saying. If they aren’t actively and radically trying to change healthcare, they need to go. 

Healthcare workers are a HUGE voter base. Politicians like to use healthcare workers as a prop for photo ops and marketing. Well that stuff comes at a cost bb. 💅

The price: politicians cannot take money from the American Hospital Association, they will fight for federal nurse to patient ratios, they actively support Medicare for all, they fight for workplace violence prevention, they fight for access to mental healthcare, they want HCWs leading the hospital. 

OTHERWISE, they need to GO. 

Nurses don’t play, let’s start calling these folks out by name..
Solidarity with the Kaiser workers on strike, let’s breakdown how they were able to achieve this massive action. 💪
Legend has it, it’s in central supply but you’ll get lost on the way down there. 🐴🧙‍♀️🪄🎆

When nurses go on strike, we are collectively taking a stand for fair wages, working conditions, and patient safety. 

By crossing the picket line travelers are undermining the principles of workplace democracy, and ultimately extend the labor dispute. 

Kaiser received a 10-day notice about the strike. They chose not to reduce census, and continue bargaining in bad faith. Kaiser put patients at risk by continuing to admit patients while stalling bargaining. They should be doing everything in their power to get the nurses who KNOW those units back on the floor. 

I know there’s a big debate about using the word “scab”… I’m not going to get into that here. We need to start thinking beyond that conversation. 

The reality is, we are having the largest labor wave of our lifetime. 

We need to support and uplift our profession and EVERYONE in healthcare. 

Travelers, we need you to support local union nurses. These are nurses who may have kids, family nearby, or other reasons they can’t/don’t want to travel. 

Union contract wins affect all nurses, including your future wages, ratios, and assignments. 

Let’s stand in solidarity as nurses and healthcare workers, and reject strike contracts.
Who’s striking and why?

Thank you so much to @thewomed for having me on to talk about workplace violence and our upcoming trip to DC! @jackiethednp and @dmmaltby will be attending, to help us advocate for workplace violence prevention and safe staffing!

1800 employees are on strike at Prime owned St. Francis Hospital. Nurses say the ratios are unsafe. Ultrasound Techs are working 18 hour days. 

Staff is saying the are EXTREMELY short staffed. 

Prime Healthcare bought St. Francis during the pandemic due to bankruptcy and LAID-OFF about 20% of their staff… in 2020. 

When large systems acquire smaller hospitals they are less responsive to community needs and more willing to eliminate services like OB & NICU.

THIS WAS PREVENTABLE. The hospital workers SAW this coming. 

These are our communities. 

It’s time for Healthcare Workers to take back medicine. 

Solidarity to the striking HCWs at @unacuhcp and @seiuuhw 💪

Prime bought Saint Francis in 2020 and laid off 20% of the folks in that hospital. 

Of course, everyone who was working in the hospital said this is a bad idea. 

They said, “we’re already struggling to provide patient care. We need more support not less.”

Now look at what’s happening, the healthcare workers are being forced to strike because of chronic understaffing. 

It’s not just nursing, it’s lab, ultrasound, ED, ICU, everybody is saying the exact same thing: that they need help, this is unsafe for our patients. 

This is the problem when you have these mergers or when these giant hospital systems buy up these small community systems, it makes it a lot easier for the hospital system to reduce staff and to reduce services like OB, L&D, NICU… because they don’t live and work in these communities. 

This is a business tactic that we have been seeing for some time now. These giant hospital systems are coming in, buying struggling community hospitals, it’s creating barriers to care, it’s creating monopolies, it also ensures that the cost will go up for the patient. Because when you have one dominant monopoly in an area, or sprinkled all over a state, they can collectively negotiate with the insurance companies for a higher reimbursement rate. 

These are our communities, we live and work in these communities. 

It’s time for healthcare workers to take medicine back.
